    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Certainly, I understand your concerns about security. The \"third party\" in an escrow arrangement is typically a licensed escrow company, which is a separate entity from the banks that hold the funds. These companies specialize in managing escrow accounts and ensuring that all conditions of the real estate transaction are met before releasing funds. They are regulated by state laws and must adhere to strict guidelines to protect both buyers and sellers. When choosing an escrow company, it's important to look for one that is reputable, well-established, and has a good track record. You can also check with your real estate agent, as they often have experience with trustworthy escrow companies and can recommend one that has worked well in the past. It's also a good idea to read reviews and possibly even check with your state's real estate commission for any complaints or disciplinary actions against the company. By doing your due diligence, you can help ensure that your money is in safe hands throughout the closing process.",
